No complete count is kept of suicide attempts in the U.S.; however, each year the CDC (Center for diesies control prevention) gathers data from hospitals on non-fatal injuries from self-harm as well as survey data.

rr c1<- who%>% group_by(country) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides))

rr c1

From this I saw that about half the countries had a suicide total over 10000 then went down all the way to Montserrat which had 1 also another fact was that about 70 percent of the countries had at least 5 years of usable data recorded.

rr whoDF_s1 <- who %>% group_by(country) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(whoDF_s1,aes(x=reorder(country,-total_suicides),y=total_suicides,fill=-total_suicides))+ geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))+ labs(x=,y=,title=-wise Suicides Stats)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

So with the first attept to look at the data it was a mess so I decided to just look at countries in terms of age and gender with regards to suicide.

rr TC <- who %>% select(country, year, sex, age, suicides_no, population,) %>% filter(country %in% c(Federation,States of America,,,,,of Korea,,,Kingdom ))

rr whoDF_sa <- who %>% group_by(age) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(whoDF_sa,aes(x=reorder(age,-total_suicides),y=total_suicides,fill=-total_suicides))+ geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))+ labs(x=,y=,title= Age Suicides Stats)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

So one of the suprising things was the age the age that had the greatest number of suicides was middle aged men.

rr whoDF_sb <- who %>% group_by(sex) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(whoDF_sb,aes(x=reorder(sex,-total_suicides),y=total_suicides,fill=-total_suicides))+ geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))+ labs(x=,y=,title=by Gender)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

rr whoDF_s3 <- who %>% group_by(year,country) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(whoDF_s3,aes(x=year,y=total_suicides,fill=-total_suicides))+ geom_col() + labs(x=,y=,title=Worldwide)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

The weird drop in Russia and Poland was caused by Na’s and zeros.

rr hop <- df7 %>% group_by(year,country) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(data = hop, mapping = aes(x =country , y = total_suicides)) + geom_boxplot() + coord_flip()

While Russia and the USA had the highest sum of suicides another important way to look at this issue is with the ratio of population.

rr df_country_group <- who %>% group_by(country) %>% summarise(sumsui= sum( as.numeric(suicides_no)),popsum = sum(as.numeric(population))) df_country_group <- na.omit(df_country_group) df_country_group_ratio<- df_country_group %>% mutate(ratioSP =sumsui/popsum) df_country_group_ratio <- df_country_group_ratio %>% arrange(-ratioSP) df_country_group_ratio_top <- head(df_country_group_ratio,10)

rr df_country_group_ratio_top1 <- df_country_group_ratio_top %>% arrange(ratioSP) ggplot(df_country_group_ratio_top1,aes(x = ratioSP, y = country )) + scale_y_discrete(limits= df_country_group_ratio_top1$country) + geom_segment( aes(xend=0,yend=country),size = 1,color=‘red2’)+ geom_point(fill=2,color=,size=4,shape=21,stroke=2) + ggtitle(with highest suicide to population ratio)+ labs(x=: Suicide/Population, y=)

 

sum(who$suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)

rr whoDF_s4 <- who %>% group_by(year,age) %>%

summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(whoDF_s4,aes(x=year,y=total_suicides,fill=age))+ geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))+ labs(x=,y=,title=Suicide Rates - Year and Age-group)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

What one sees is that there is spike in the late 90’s then a slight decrease and increase around 2007-2008 then a continued decrease.

also the gap in the years of 84 and 85 are coused by the russian Data

I wanted to finally compare the 2 countries with highest suicide by sum, the USA and Russia.

rr whoDF_s3 <- who %>% filter(country ==States of America) %>% group_by(year) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(whoDF_s3,aes(x=year,y=total_suicides,fill=-total_suicides))+ geom_col() + labs(x=,y=,title=in USA)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

rr whoDF_s3 <- who %>% filter(country == Federation) %>% group_by(year) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(whoDF_s3,aes(x=year,y=total_suicides,fill=-total_suicides))+ geom_col() + labs(x=,y=,title=in Russia)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

rr whoDF_s4 <- who %>% filter(country == States of America) %>% group_by(year,age) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(whoDF_s4,aes(x=year,y=total_suicides,fill=age))+ geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))+ labs(x=,y=,title=in USA - Year and Age-group)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

rr whoDF_s4 <- who %>% filter(country == Federation) %>% group_by(year,age) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) %>% arrange(desc(total_suicides)) ggplot(whoDF_s4,aes(x=year,y=total_suicides,fill=age))+ geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))+ labs(x=,y=,title=in Russia - Year and Age-group)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

rr whoDF_s6 <- who %>% filter(country == Federation,year%in%c(997,015,980)) %>% group_by(sex,age,year) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) ggplot(whoDF_s6,aes(x=factor(age,levels = c(-14 years,5-24 years,5-34 years,5-54 years,5-74 years,5+ years)),y=total_suicides,fill=sex))+ geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))+ facet_wrap(whoDF_s6$year) + labs(x=,y=,title=in Russia in 2015)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

rr whoDF_s7 <- who %>% filter(country == States of America,year%in%c(997,015,980)) %>% group_by(sex,age,year) %>% summarise(total_suicides = sum(suicides_no,na.rm=TRUE)) ggplot(whoDF_s7,aes(x=factor(age,levels = c(-14 years,5-24 years,5-34 years,5-54 years,5-74 years,5+ years)),y=total_suicides,fill=sex))+ geom_col() + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))+ facet_wrap(whoDF_s6$year) + labs(x=,y=,title=in USA)+ theme(plot.title = element_text(size=15,face=))

In 2015, 505,507 people visited a hospital for injuries due to self-harm. This number suggests that for every reported suicide death, approximately 11.4 people visit a hospital for self-harm related injuries. However, because of the way these data are collected, we are not able to distinguish intentional suicide attempts from non-intentional self-harm behaviors.

Based on the 2016 National Survey of Drug Use and Mental Health it is estimated that 0.5 percent of the adults aged 18 or older made at least one suicide attempt. This translates to approximately 1.3 million adults. Adult females reported a suicide attempt 1.2 times as often as males. Further breakdown by gender and race are not available.

Based on the 2015 Youth Risk Behaviors Survey, 8.6 percent of youth in grades 9-12 reported that they had made at least one suicide attempt in the past 12 months. Girls attempted twice as often as boys (11.6% vs. 5.5%) and teens of Hispanic origin reported the highest rate of attempt (11.3%), especially Hispanic females (15.1%) when compared with white students (6.8%) and White females (9.8%). Approximately 2.8 percent reported making a suicide attempt that required treatment by a doctor or nurse. For those requiring treatment, rates were highest for Hispanic students with black males (4.0%) and Hispanic males (2.9%) having higher rates than white male (0.9%) students.

When it comes to suicide and suicide attempts there are rate differences depending on demographic characteristics such as age, gender, ethnicity and race. Nonetheless, suicide occurs in all demographic groups.

American foundation for for prevention of suicide
